<paragraph id="8B89BE4BFF89FFB57DE6C331FE1129A4" blockId="19.[151,399,872,899]" box="[151,399,872,899]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<heading id="D0C10927FF89FFB57DE6C331FE1129A4" bold="true" box="[151,399,872,899]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" reason="1">
<taxonomicName id="4C36C5C8FF89FFB57DE6C331FE1129A4" authority="Bangs" authorityName="Bangs" box="[151,399,872,899]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Oligoryzomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9426259FF89FFB57DE6C331FE1129A4" bold="true" box="[151,399,872,899]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis id="B9426259FF89FFB57DE6C331FEA529A5" bold="true" box="[151,315,873,899]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Oligoryzomys</emphasis>
Bangs
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B89BE4BFF89FFB57DE6C3E8FF532E7E" blockId="19.[151,1436,943,1472]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<taxonomicName id="4C36C5C8FF89FFB57DE6C3E8FEAD29EE" box="[151,307,944,968]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Oligoryzomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9426259FF89FFB57DE6C3E8FEAD29EE" box="[151,307,944,968]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Oligoryzomys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was the smallest mammal encountered in the area. The dorsal pelage is tawny yellow-brown streaked with black hairs, sides become lighter and the ventral pelage varies from buff to light orange. Heads of both species captured in the study area are grayish and ears are covered by small light hairs. The tail is longer than the head and body length and is self-colored. 
<collectingCountry id="F321FEDBFF89FFB57FE2C444FD552E12" box="[659,715,1052,1076]" name="India" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Hind</collectingCountry>
feet are narrow and very long. Females have four pairs of mammae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B89BE4BFF89FFB57DB4C43CFCF92FE6" blockId="19.[151,1436,943,1472]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Phylogenetic analyses based on 
<emphasis id="B9426259FF89FFB57F40C43CFDF72E5A" box="[561,617,1124,1148]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">cyt-b</emphasis>
sequence data allow us to recognize two species among PEC specimens (
<figureCitation id="130DA2CEFF89FFB57DEEC4DFFF6C2EB9" box="[159,242,1159,1183]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1243,1266]" captionTargetBox="[449,1138,376,1217]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[443,1144,363,1222]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 10. Bayesian tree of cyt-b haplotypes from specimens of Oligoryzomys rooted using Hylaeamys and Thomasomys. Bayesian posterior probabilities are in bold and percentages are average Kimura two-parameter distances." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/206251/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Fig. 
<number id="3DFEAC6CFF89FFB57DA2C4DFFF6C2EB9" box="[211,242,1159,1183]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
). Specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C36C5C8FF89FFB57CD5C4D0FD8B2E86" box="[420,533,1160,1184]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Oligoryzomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fornesi">
<emphasis id="B9426259FF89FFB57CD5C4D0FD8B2E86" box="[420,533,1160,1184]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<collectingCountry id="F321FEDBFF89FFB57CD5C4D0FE252EB9" box="[420,443,1160,1183]" name="Iceland" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">O</collectingCountry>
. fornesi
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
form a monophyletic clade, grouping samples from the study area (
<collectionCode id="ED27268EFF89FFB57878C4DFFAD12EB9" box="[1289,1359,1159,1183]" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/n6nq-8nqh" name="Universidade Federal do Espirito Santo" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">UFES</collectionCode>
<number id="3DFEAC6CFF89FFB57827C4DFFF512EE2" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="1372.0" valueMax="1373.0" valueMin="1371.0">
<date id="FF88988BFF89FFB57827C4DFFF512EE2" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="1371" valueMax="1373">1371â€“ 1373</date>
</number>
and 
<collectionCode id="ED27268EFF89FFB57C78C4F4FED32EE2" box="[265,333,1196,1220]" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/n6nq-8nqh" name="Universidade Federal do Espirito Santo" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">UFES</collectionCode>
<number id="3DFEAC6CFF89FFB57C27C4F4FE4B2EE2" box="[342,469,1196,1220]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="1440.5" valueMax="1441.0" valueMin="1440.0">
<date id="FF88988BFF89FFB57C27C4F4FE4B2EE2" box="[342,469,1196,1220]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="1440" valueMax="1441">1440â€“1441</date>
</number>
) and those from the Cerrado areas in the state of GoiÃ¡s (MN 
<number id="3DFEAC6CFF89FFB579E8C4F4FB412EE2" box="[1177,1247,1196,1220]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="36746.0">36746</number>
and MN 
<number id="3DFEAC6CFF89FFB5783EC4F4FA062EE2" box="[1359,1432,1196,1220]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="36928.0">36928</number>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA7C3BAFF89FFB57DE6C497FEE72EC1" author="Miranda" box="[151,377,1231,1256]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" refString="Miranda, G. B., Oliveira, L. F. B, Andrades-Miranda, J., Langguth, A., Callegari-Jacques, S. M. &amp; Mattevi, M. (2009) Phylogenetics and phylogeographic patterns in sigmodontine rodents of the genus Oligoryzomys. Journal of Heredity, 100, 309 - 321." type="journal article" year="2009">
Miranda 
<emphasis id="B9426259FF89FFB57D8CC489FEB02ECE" box="[253,302,1232,1256]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number id="3DFEAC6CFF89FFB57C4CC497FEE72EC1" box="[317,377,1231,1255]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="2009.0">2009</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), with an average intraclade divergence of 1.6% among them. The specimen that we treat here as 
<taxonomicName id="4C36C5C8FF89FFB57DC5C4ACFECE2F2A" box="[180,336,1268,1292]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Oligoryzomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9426259FF89FFB57DC5C4ACFECE2F2A" box="[180,336,1268,1292]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Oligoryzomys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. groups with 
<taxonomicName id="4C36C5C8FF89FFB57F79C4ADFD1B2F2A" box="[520,645,1269,1292]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Oligoryzomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="microtis">
<emphasis id="B9426259FF89FFB57F79C4ADFD1B2F2A" box="[520,645,1269,1292]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<collectingCountry id="F321FEDBFF89FFB57F79C4ADFD812F2A" box="[520,543,1269,1292]" name="Iceland" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">O</collectingCountry>
. microtis
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from state of Amazonas, 
<collectingCountry id="F321FEDBFF89FFB57ED2C4ACFC792F2A" box="[931,999,1268,1292]" name="Brazil" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(Patton 
<emphasis id="B9426259FF89FFB57934C4ADFBE82F2A" box="[1093,1142,1268,1292]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number id="3DFEAC6CFF89FFB579F2C4ACFB232F2A" box="[1155,1213,1268,1292]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="2000.0">2000</number>
) and from 
<collectingCountry id="F321FEDBFF89FFB57846C4ADFAF32F2A" box="[1335,1389,1269,1292]" name="Peru" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Peru</collectingCountry>
, but with high divergence between them (7.7%). This high divergence probably reflects two distinct species, but with limited samples, we are unable to rule out the possibility of isolation by distance in a geographically structured species. More samples of these species from eastern Amazonia are needed to clarify their taxonomic identities. Nevertheless, our molecular data corroborates previous authors, who found that 
<taxonomicName id="4C36C5C8FF89FFB57E84C5DDFBF72FBA" box="[1013,1129,1412,1436]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Oligoryzomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fornesi">
<emphasis id="B9426259FF89FFB57E84C5DDFBF72FBA" box="[1013,1129,1412,1436]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<collectingCountry id="F321FEDBFF89FFB57E84C5DDFB922FBA" box="[1013,1036,1413,1436]" name="Iceland" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">O</collectingCountry>
. fornesi
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C36C5C8FF89FFB579D4C5DDFABB2FBA" box="[1189,1317,1413,1436]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Oligoryzomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="microtis">
<emphasis id="B9426259FF89FFB579D4C5DDFABB2FBA" box="[1189,1317,1413,1436]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<collectingCountry id="F321FEDBFF89FFB579D4C5DDFB222FBA" box="[1189,1212,1413,1436]" name="Iceland" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">O</collectingCountry>
. microtis
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belong to distinct and divergent evolutionary lineages (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA7C3BAFF89FFB57FFEC5F0FCC42FE6" author="Myers" box="[655,858,1448,1472]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" refString="Myers, P., Lundrigan, B. &amp; Tucker, P. K. (1995) Molecular phylogenetics of Oryzomyine rodents: the genus Oligoryzomys. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 4, 372 - 382." type="journal article" year="1995">
Myers 
<emphasis id="B9426259FF89FFB57FAEC5F1FC892FE6" box="[735,791,1448,1472]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">et al.</emphasis>
<number id="3DFEAC6CFF89FFB57E6FC5F0FCC42FE6" box="[798,858,1448,1472]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="1995.0">1995</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
